 0055: # NOTES ON ERROR HANDLING
 0056: # If an error occurs within a connection object, the error may - depending
 0057: # on the error code - affect the status of the connection object.
 0058: # Therefore, the _error() method is called instead of raising the error
 0059: # directly.
 0060: # However, updating the connection status is not possible in the
 0061: # fill/wrap-functions, as there is no connection object available. But this
 0062: # should not be a problem as we do not expect connection-affecting errors if
 0063: # no connection is present.

 0091:     """ A connection to an SAP backend system
 0092: 
 0093:     Instantiating an :class:`pyrfc.Connection` object will
 0094:     automatically attempt to open a connection the SAP backend.
 0095: 
 0096:     :param config: Configuration of the instance. Allowed keys are:
 0097: 
 0098:            ``dtime``
 0099:              returns datetime types (accepts strings and datetimes), default is False
 0100:            ``rstrip``
 0101:              right strips strings returned from RFC call (default is True)
 0102:            ``return_import_params``
 0103:              importing parameters are returned by the RFC call (default is False)
 0104: 
 0105:     :type config: dict or None (default)
 0106: 
 0107:     :param params: SAP connection parameters. The parameters consist of
 0108:            ``client``, ``user``, ``passwd``, ``lang``, ``trace``
 0109:            and additionally one of
 0110: 
 0111:            * Direct application server logon: ``ashost``, ``sysnr``.
 0112:            * Logon with load balancing: ``mshost``, ``msserv``, ``sysid``,
 0113:              ``group``.
 0114:              ``msserv`` is needed only, if the service of the message server
 0115:              is not defined as sapms<SYSID> in /etc/services.
 0116:            * When logging on with SNC, ``user`` and ``passwd`` are to be replaced by
 0117:              ``snc_qop``, ``snc_myname``, ``snc_partnername``, and optionally
 0118:              ``snc_lib``.
 0119:              (If ``snc_lib`` is not specified, the RFC library uses the "global" GSS library
 0120:              defined via environment variable SNC_LIB.)
 0121: 
 0122:     :type params: Keyword parameters
 0123: 
 0124:     :raises: :exc:`~pyrfc.RFCError` or a subclass
 0125:              thereof if the connection attempt fails.
 0126:     """

static char __pyx_doc_5pyrfc_6_pyrfc_10Connection_54fill_and_submit_unit[] = " Fills a unit with one or more RFC and submits it to the backend.\n\n        Fills a unit for this connection, prepare the invocation\n        of multiple RFC function modules in it, and submits the unit\n        to the backend.\n\n        Afterwards, the unit is still attached to the connection object,\n        until confirm_unit() or destroy_unit() is called. Until one of these\n        methods are called, no other unit could be filled and submitted.\n\n        :param unit: a unit descriptor as returned by\n               :meth:`~pyrfc.Connection.initialize_unit`.\n        :param calls: a list of call descriptions. Each call description is a\n               tuple that contains the function name as the first element and\n               the function arguments in form of a dictionary as the second element.\n        :param queue_names:\n               If the unit uses the background protocol, various queue names can\n               be given (leading to a asynchronous unit, type 'Q'). If parameter\n               is an empty list or None, a synchronous unit (type 'T') is created.\n\n               If the unit does not use the background protocol, the queue name\n               may be a list with exactly one element, leading to a qRFC, or\n               an empty list or None, leading to a tRFC.\n        :type queue_names: list of strings or None (default)\n        :param attributes: optional argument for attributes of the unit -- only valid if the background protocol\n              is used. The attributes dict may contain the following keywords:\n\n              =============== ============================= ======================= ==========================================================================================\n              keyword         default                       type                    description\n              =============== ============================= ======================= =======================================================================""===================\n              kernel_trace    0                             int                     If != 0, the backend will write kernel traces, while executing this unit.\n              sat_trace       0                             int                     If != 0, the backend will write statistic records, while executing this unit.\n              unit_history    0                             int                     If != 0, the backend will keep a \"history\" for this unit.\n              lock            0                             int                     Used only for type Q: If != 0, the unit will be written to the queue, but not processed.\n                                                                                    The unit can then be started manually in the ABAP debugger.\n              no_commit_check 0                             int                     Per default the backend will check during execution of a unit, whether one of the\n                                                                                    unit's function modules triggers an explicit or implicit COMMITWORK.\n                                                                                    In this case the unit is aborted with an error, because the transactional integrity of\n                                                                                    this unit cannot be guaranteed. By setting \"no_commit_check\" to true (!=0), this behavior\n                                                                                    can be suppressed, meaning the unit will be executed anyway, even if one of it's\n                                                                                    function modules \"misbehaves\" and triggers a COMMIT WORK.\n              user            current operating system user String, len |nbsp| 12   Sender User (optional).\n              client          \"000\"                         String, len |nbsp| 3    Sender Client (""\"Mandant\") (optional).\n              t_code          \"\"                            String, len |nbsp| 20   Sender Transaction Code (optional).\n              program         current executable name       String, len |nbsp| 40   Sender Program (optional).\n              =============== ============================= ======================= ==========================================================================================\n\n        :type attributes: dict or None (default)\n        :raises: :exc:`~pyrfc.RFCError` or a subclass thereof if an error\n                 occurred. In this case, the unit is destroyed.\n        ";

 1243:     """ An SAP server
 1244: 
 1245:     An instance of :class:`~pyrfc.Server` allows for installing
 1246:     Python callback functions and serve requests from SAP systems.
 1247: 
 1248:     :param config: Configuration of the instance. Allowed keys are:
 1249: 
 1250:            ``rstrip``
 1251:              right strips strings passed to Python callback
 1252:              functions. (default is True)
 1253:            ``debug``
 1254:              For testing/debugging operations. If True, the server
 1255:              behaves more permissive, e.g. allows incoming calls without a
 1256:              valid connection handle. (default is False)
 1257: 
 1258:     :type config: dict or None (default)
 1259:     :param params: Parameters for registering the server.
 1260:                    The parameters may contain the following keywords:
 1261:                    ``GWHOST``, ``GWSERV``, ``PROGRAM_ID``, ``TRACE``,
 1262:                    and ``SAPROUTER``.
 1263:     :type params: Keyword parameters
 1264: 
 1265:     :raises: :exc:`~pyrfc.RFCError` or a subclass
 1266:              thereof if the connection attempt fails.
